04509nam a22007215i 9781501726583DE-B159720190430100931.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190430s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017265837 a10.7591/97815017265832doi  a(DE-B1597)515621  a(OCoLC)1100462960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ766.5.C6bW485 2006eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh 7aPOL0290002bisacsh 7aSOC0260102bisacsh04a363.9/609512231 aWhite, Tyrene, eauthor.10aChina's Longest Campaign :bBirth Planning in the People's Republic, 1949-2005 /cTyrene White. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource :b10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- t1. The Collectivization of Childbearing -- t2. Jihua Shengyu: The Origins of Birth Planning -- t3. Planning Population Growth: The Political Economy of State Intervention -- t4. The Architecture of Mobilization -- t5. Two Kinds of Production: Rural Reform and the One-Child Campaign -- t6. The Politics of Mass Sterilization -- t7. Strategies of Resistance -- t8. Campaign Revivalism and Its Limits -- t9. Against the Grain: The Chinese Experience with Birth Planning -- tReferences -- tIndex  aIn the late 1970s, just as China was embarking on a sweeping program of post-Mao reforms, it also launched a one-child campaign. This campaign, which cut against the grain of rural reforms and childbearing preferences, was the culmination of a decade-long effort to subject reproduction to state planning. Tyrene White here analyzes this great social engineering experiment, drawing on more than twenty years of research, including fieldwork and interviews with a wide range of family-planning officials and rural cadres.White explores the origins of China's "birth-planning" approach to population control, the implementation of the campaign in rural China, strategies of resistance employed by villagers, and policy consequences (among them infanticide, infant abandonment, and sex-ratio imbalances). She also provides the first extensive political analysis of China's massive 1983 sterilization drive. The birth-planning project was the last and longest of the great mobilization campaigns, surviving long after the Deng regime had officially abandoned mass campaigns as instruments of political control.Arguing that the campaign had become an indispensable institution of rural governance, White shows how the one-child campaign mimicked the organizational style and rhythms both of political campaigns and economic production campaigns. Against the backdrop of unfolding rural reforms, only the campaign method could override obstacles to rural enforcement. As reform gradually eroded and transformed patterns of power and authority, however, even campaigns grew increasingly ineffective, paving the way for long-overdue reform of the birth-planning program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Apr 2019) 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501726583.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG